New Rules for the Global Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let's imagine that the leading world politicians would once again meet in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new global economic order.
They would naturally focus primarily on today's problems: the Eurozone crisis, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. However, addressing these issues would force the assembled leaders to go beyond them and reconsider the overall solidity of global economic arrangements.
Here are seven common-sense principles for global economic management that they might possibly agree on.
(I discuss these in more detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. The markets must be deeply embedded in existing control systems.
The idea that markets regulate themselves has suffered a fatal blow through the recent financial crisis and should be permanently buried.
Markets need other societal institutions that support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies that establish and enforce rules.
They depend on the stabilization functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
You need the political acceptance that is generated by redistributive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all of this applies equally to global markets.
2. In the foreseeable future, a democratic state leadership will remain largely organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives on, even if it may be somewhat weakened, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is futile.
Dass national governments transfer significant control power to transnational institutions is hardly foreseeable; moreover, a harmonization of rules would be of no benefit to societies with differing needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis seems to contradict this.
We too often waste international cooperation on overly ambitious goals. In the end, weak results emerge, representing the smallest common denominator among the major countries.
If international cooperation is "successful," it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel rules on capital requirements and the WTO rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures typify this kind of overly ambitious ambition.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic procedures in our own country, rather than destroying them.

3. Pluralistic prosperity: The acknowledgment that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best suit their needs.
The USA, Europe, and Japan have long-term comparable prosperity.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social security, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models" – one in each decade – is then presented as the great success to which one should aspire.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experiments and permit further evolution of their institutions.
A world economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will tend to foster such experimental enthusiasm and evolutionary development rather than suppress them.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may seem innocuous.
But they carry powerful implications that clash with the prevailing views of globalization supporters.
An implication of this kind is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries were not provided with the instruments to shape and preserve their own institutions – in other words, to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries may retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect consumer health and safety – and that they should be allowed to do so by possibly erecting barriers at their borders when trade is proven to threaten domestic practices that enjoy wide public support.
If advocates of globalization are right, the call for such protective measures will fail due to lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve to ensure that conflicting values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of retaining national regulations – can both be adequately heard in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to preserve values and rules within their own country must not be confused with the use of such restrictions to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries would find unacceptable.
Similarly, they should not allow the US or the EU to use trade sanctions or other forms of pressure to change labor market rules, environmental policies, or financial regulations in other countries.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to forced convergence.

6. International economic agreements on the regulation of the interaction between national institutions: Relying on the national states to provide the basic control functions of the world economy does not mean that we should do without international rules.
The Bretton Woods system had clear rules in the end, even though they were limited in scope and depth.
A completely catch-as-catch-can approach would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the world economy, which help vehicles of different size, shape, and speed to pass each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive to achieve a maximum of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot claim the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where this actually occurs, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
Für undemokratische Staaten müssen also andere, weniger freizügige Regeln gelten.
Dies sind die Prinzipien, die die Architekten der nächsten Weltwirtschaftsordnung akzeptieren müssen.
Am wichtigsten ist dabei, dass sie das letztendliche Paradoxon akzeptieren müssen, das jedes dieser Prinzipien illustriert: Globalisierung funktioniert am besten, wenn man es damit nicht zu weit treibt.
